{{Other uses|Internet in a Box (disambiguation)}} {{Infobox software | title = | logo = <!-- Image name is enough --> | logo caption = | logo size = | logo alt = | screenshot = <!-- Image name is enough --> | caption = | screenshot size = | screenshot alt = | collapsible = | author = | developer = | released = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} --> | discontinued = | latest release version = | latest release date = {{Start date and age|2014|10|15|df=yes/no}} | latest preview version = | latest preview date = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} --> | status = | programming language = | operating system = | platform = | size = | language = | language count = <!-- Number only --> | language footnote = | genre = | license = [[GNU GPL]] | alexa = | website = {{URL|https://www.commotionwireless.net/}} | standard = }}
'''Commotion Wireless''' is an [[open-source software|open-source]] [[wireless]] [[mesh network]] for electronic communication.<ref name=gigaom>{{cite web |url =http://gigaom.com/2012/12/18/detroit-is-the-testing-ground-for-a-new-open-source-wireless-network-technology/ |title =Detroit is the testing ground for a new open source wireless network technology |last =Higginbotham |first =Stacey |date = 18 December 2012 |work = [[GigaOM]] |publisher = |accessdate = }}</ref><ref name=fierce>{{cite web |url =http://www.fiercebroadbandwireless.com/story/first-detroit-then-world-commotion-mesh-networking/2012-12-19 |title =First Detroit, then the world for Commotion mesh networking |last = Parker |first = Tammy |date = 19 December 2012 |work = Fierce Broadband Wireless |publisher = |accessdate =7 March 2013 }}</ref> The project was developed by the [[Open Technology Institute]], and development included a $2 million grant from the [[United States Department of State]] in 2011 for use as a [[mobile ad hoc network]] (MANET), concomitant with the [[Arab Spring]].<ref name=spectrum>{{cite web |url =http://spectrum.ieee.org/telecom/internet/building-a-subversive-grassroots-network |title =Building a Subversive Grassroots Network |author =Ritchie S. King |date = July 2011 |work = Spectrum |publisher = [[Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers]] |accessdate = 7 March 2013 }}</ref>{{Third-party-inline|date=March 2013}} It was preliminarily deployed in [[Detroit]] in late 2012,<ref name=gigaom /><ref name=fierce /> and launched generally in March 2013.<ref name=demonow>{{cite web |url =http://www.democracynow.org/2013/3/5/sharing_the_internet_new_commotion_wireless |title =Sharing the Internet: "Commotion Wireless" Technology Lets Communities Create Free Webs of Access |last = Goodman |first = Amy |date = 5 March 2013 |work = [[Democracy Now]] |publisher = |accessdate = 7 March 2013 }}</ref> The project has been called an "Internet in a Suitcase".<ref name=nytimes>{{cite web |url =https://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/12/world/12internet.html?_r=1 |title =U.S. Underwrites Internet Detour Around Censors |author =James Glanz and John Markoff |date = 12 June 2011 |publisher = [[New York Times]] |accessdate = 23 April 2013 }}</ref><ref name=yahoo>{{cite web |url = https://news.yahoo.com/iran-says-block-internet-suitcase-180900065.html |title = Iran says it can block 'Internet in a suitcase' |author = [[Associated Press]] |date = 15 July 2011 |publisher = [[Yahoo News]] |accessdate = 23 April 2013 }}</ref>
Commotion 1.0, the first non-[[Software release life cycle#Beta|beta]] release, was launched on December 30, 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newamerica.org/node/99668 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-01-01 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102200713/http://www.newamerica.org/node/99668 |archivedate=2014-01-02 |df= }}</ref>
Commotion relies on several open source projects: [[Optimized Link State Routing Protocol|OLSR]], [[OpenWrt]], [[OpenBTS]], and [[Serval project]].<ref>http://www.commotionwireless.net/about/faq</ref>
